   "source": [
    "plt.plot(data[:, 0], data[:, 1], '.')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('duration')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('interval')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can clearly see two clusters here.  For higher dimensional data, we cannot directly visualize the data to see the clusters.  We need a mathematical way to detect clusters. This gives rise to the class of unsupervised learning methods called *clustering* algorithms.\n",
    "\n",
    "A simple example of a clustering algorithm is the *k-means* algorithm.  It results in identifying $k$ cluster centers.  It is an iterative algorithm that starts with an initial assignment of $k$ centers.  Then it proceeds by determining which centers each data sample is closest to and adjusts the centers to be the means of each of these data partitions.  It then repeats.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's develop this algorithm one step at a time."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Each sample is the Old Faithful data has 2 attributes, so each sample is in 2-dimensional space.  We know by looking at the above plot that our data nicely falls in two clusters, so we will start with $k=2$.  We will initialize the two cluster centers by randomly choosing two of the data samples."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.341683Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.338244Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([ 26, 238])"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "n_samples = data.shape[0]\n",
    "np.random.choice(range(n_samples), 2, replace=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "However, we can ask numpy to do this duplication for us if we reshape `a` to be a column vector and leave `b` as a row vector.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ \\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "1\\\\\n",
    "2\\\\\n",
    "3\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix}\n",
    "-\n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "10 & 20 & 30\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix}\n",
    "\\;\\; = \\;\\;\n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "1 & 1 & 1\\\\\n",
    "2 & 2 & 2\\\\\n",
    "3 & 3 & 3\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix}\n",
    "-\n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "10 & 20 & 30\\\\\n",
    "10 & 20 & 30\\\\\n",
    "10 & 20 & 30\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix}\n",
    "$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.389814Z",

    }

    "Now imagine that `a` is a cluster center and `b` contains data samples, one per row.  The first step of calculating the distance from `a` to all samples in `b` is to subtract them component-wise."
   ]

   "source": [
    "centers"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we can wrap these steps in our first version of a `kmeans` function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.489506Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.486134Z"
    },
    "code_folding": []
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def kmeans(data, k = 2, n_iterations = 5):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Initial centers\n",
    "    centers = data[np.random.choice(range(data.shape[0]), k, replace=False), :]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Repeat n times\n",
    "    for iteration in range(n_iterations):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Which center is each sample closest to?\n",
    "        closest = np.argmin(np.sum((centers[:, np.newaxis, :] - data)**2, axis=2), axis=0)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Update cluster centers\n",
    "        for i in range(k):\n",
    "            centers[i, :] = data[closest == i, :].mean(axis=0)\n",
    "            \n",
    "    return centers"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.496107Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.490926Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([[ 2.09433   , 54.75      ],\n",
       "       [ 4.29793023, 80.28488372]])"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 31,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }

   "source": [
    "kmeans(data, 2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.501288Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.497163Z"

   ],
   "source": [
    "kmeans(data, 2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We need a measure of the quality of our clustering.  For this, we define $J$, which is a performance measure being minimized by *k-means*. It is defined as\n",
    "$$\n",
    "J = \\sum_{n=1}^N \\sum_{k=1}^K r_{nk} ||\\mathbf{x}_n - \\mathbf{\\mu}_k||^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "where $N$ is the number of samples, $K$ is the number of cluster centers, $\\mathbf{x}_n$ is the $n^{th}$ sample and $\\mathbf{\\mu}_k$ is the $k^{th}$ center, each being an element of $\\mathbf{R}^p$ where $p$ is the dimensionality of the data. $r_{nk}$ is 1 if $\\mathbf{x}_n$ is closest to center $\\mathbf{\\mu}_k$, and 0 otherwise.\n",
    "\n",
    "The sums can be computed using python *for* loops, but, as you know, *for* loops are much slower than matrix operations in python, so let's do the matrix magic. We already know how to calculate the difference between all samples and all centers."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 33,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.506598Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.502393Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "(2, 272)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 33,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sqdists = np.sum((centers[:,np.newaxis,:] - data)**2, axis=2)\n",
    "sqdists.shape"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The calculation of $J$ requires us to multiply the squared differences of the each component by $r_{nk}$. Since we already have all of the squared distances, let's just sum up the minimum distances for each sample. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 34,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.514445Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.507632Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([2.73080852e+00, 1.44700255e+00, 4.30937030e+01, 4.68712915e+01,\n",

       "       1.73010559e+01, 2.03313825e+01, 1.42598475e+00, 1.24684631e+01,\n",

       "       2.37956094e+00, 1.47996239e+01, 3.03903067e+01, 9.05816996e+01,\n",
       "       1.42598475e+00, 5.12342005e-01, 1.49637504e+00, 6.62016745e+00,\n",

       "       9.02376939e+01, 6.31342154e+00, 7.31662739e-01, 2.22430946e+00,\n",

   ],
   "source": [
    "np.min(sqdists, axis=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 35,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.520349Z",

   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "8925.715281184834"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 35,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "np.sum(np.min(sqdists, axis=0))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's define a function named *calcJ* to do this calculation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 36,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.525172Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.521312Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def calcJ(data, centers):\n",
    "    sqdists = np.sum((centers[:, np.newaxis, :] - data)**2, axis=2)\n",
    "    return np.sum(np.min(sqdists, axis=0))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.531747Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.526205Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "8925.715281184834"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 37,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "calcJ(data, centers)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we can add this calculation to track the value of $J$ for each iteration as a kind of learning curve.  $J$ measures the average \"spread\" within each cluster, so the smaller it is, the better."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 38,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.538602Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.533211Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def kmeans(data, k, n_iterations):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Initialize centers and list J to track performance metric\n",
    "    centers = data[np.random.choice(range(data.shape[0]), k, replace=False), :]\n",
    "    J = []\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for iteration in range(n_iterations):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Which center is each sample closest to?\n",
    "        sqdistances = np.sum((centers[:, np.newaxis, :] - data)**2, axis=2)\n",
    "        closest = np.argmin(sqdistances, axis=0)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Calculate J and append to list J\n",
    "        J.append(calcJ(data, centers))\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Update cluster centers\n",
    "        for i in range(k):\n",
    "            centers[i, :] = data[closest == i, :].mean(axis=0)\n",
    "            \n",
    "    # Calculate J one final time and return results\n",
    "    J.append(calcJ(data, centers))\n",
    "    return centers, J, closest"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.547318Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:33:27.539865Z"
    },
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "centers, J, closest = kmeans(data, 2, 10)"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "How could you use the results of the `kmeans` clustering algorithm as the first step in a classification algorithm?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# K-Nearest-Neighbor Classification"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now that we have some experience in calculating distances between samples, we are a short step away from an implementation of a common classification algorithm called *k-nearest-neighbor*.  This is a non-parametric algorithm, meaning that it does not involve parameters, like weights, to make its decisions.  Instead, we could call it a memory-based method. The algorithm classifies a sample by determining the $k$ closest samples in the training set and returns the most common class label among those $k$ nearest samples."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Training is terribly simple.  We just have to store the training samples.  Classification is also trivial to code.  We just calculate squared distances between training samples and the samples being classified and return the most common class label among the $k$ closest training samples.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's create a class named `KNN` to implement this algorithm."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "First, let's practice our `numpy`-foo to see how to pick the most common class, with a minimum amount of code.\n",
    "\n",
    "Remember that `sqdists` from above is `n_centers` x `n_samples`.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's try to classify the first three MNIST test samples."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 61,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:37:11.521822Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:37:11.356173Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "(3, 50000)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 61,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sqdists = np.sum((Xtest[:3, np.newaxis, :] - Xtrain)**2, axis=2)\n",
    "sqdists.shape"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Okay. Now all we have to do is find the $k$ smallest distances in each row.  Let's use $k=5$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 62,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:37:11.528364Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:37:11.522838Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([ 9.6193695, 11.355759 , 11.403915 , 12.214478 , 12.627594 ],\n",
       "      dtype=float32)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 62,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "k = 5\n",
    "np.sort(sqdists[0, :])[:k]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "But, we need the indices of these values so we can look up their class labels in `T`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 63,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:37:11.536062Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:37:11.529922Z"
    }

   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([38620, 16186, 27059, 47003, 14563])"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 63,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "k = 5\n",
    "np.argsort(sqdists[0, :])[:k]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we have to do this for each row in `sqdists`.  Or do we?  Wouldn't it be nice if `np.argsort` sorts each row independently so we can do this in one function call?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 64,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:37:11.549290Z",

    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

     "execution_count": 64,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }

   "source": [

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Cool! Now we just have to take the first $k$ columns of these and determine the most common label across the columns, for each row.  We can use `scipy.stats.mode` for this!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 129,
   "metadata": {

     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:41:07.994143Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:41:07.988633Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([[7],\n",
       "       [2],\n",
       "       [1]])"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 92,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "Ttest[:3]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Well, maybe we will do better with different values of $k$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, we can now define our `KNN` class."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 93,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:41:27.212071Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:41:27.203262Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import scipy.stats as ss  # for ss.mode\n",
    "\n",
    "class KNN():\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def __init__(self):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        self.X = None  # data will be stored here\n",
    "        self.T = None  # class labels will be stored here\n",
    "        self.Xmeans = None\n",
    "        self.Xstds = None\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def train(self, X, T):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        if self.Xmeans is None:\n",
    "            self.Xmeans = X.mean(axis=0)\n",
    "            self.Xstds = X.std(axis=0)\n",
    "            self.Xstds[self.Xstds == 0] = 1\n",
    "            \n",
    "        self.X = self._standardizeX(X)\n",
    "        self.T = T\n",
    "        \n",
    "    def _standardizeX(self, X):\n",
    "        return (X - self.Xmeans) / self.Xstds\n",
    "\n",
    "    def use(self, Xnew, k = 1):\n",
    "        self.k = k\n",
    "        # Calc squared distance from all samples in Xnew with all stored in self.X\n",
    "        sqdists = np.sum( (self._standardizeX(Xnew)[:, np.newaxis, :] - self.X)**2, axis=-1 )\n",
    "        # sqdist\n",
    "\n",
    "        # sqdists is now n_new_samples x n_train_samples\n",
    "        # Sort each row of squared distances from smallest to largest and select the first k.\n",
    "        indices = np.argsort(sqdists, axis=1)[:, :k]\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Determine mose common class label in each row.\n",
    "        classes = ss.mode(self.T[indices, :][:, :, 0], axis=1, keepdims=True)[0]\n",
    "        \n",
    "        return classes"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 94,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:41:27.793554Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:41:27.789361Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [

     "data": {

       "<__main__.KNN at 0x7fb5e947af70>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 94,

    "knn = KNN()\n",
    "knn"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",

    "Oh, can't have that!!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 117,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T18:55:56.432544Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T18:55:56.424277Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import scipy.stats as ss  # for ss.mode\n",
    "\n",
    "class KNN():\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def __init__(self):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        self.X = None  # data will be stored here\n",
    "        self.T = None  # class labels will be stored here\n",
    "        self.Xmeans = None\n",
    "        self.Xstds = None\n",
    "        \n",
    "    def __repr__(self):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        if self.X is None:\n",
    "            return f'KNN() has not been trained.'\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            return f'KNN(), trained with {self.X.shape[0]} samples having class labels {np.unique(self.T)}.'\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def train(self, X, T):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        if self.Xmeans is None:\n",
    "            self.Xmeans = X.mean(axis=0)\n",
    "            self.Xstds = X.std(axis=0)\n",
    "            self.Xstds[self.Xstds == 0] = 1\n",
    "            \n",
    "        self.X = self._standardizeX(X)\n",
    "        self.T = T\n",
    "        \n",
    "        return self\n",
    "        \n",
    "    def _standardizeX(self, X):\n",
    "        return (X - self.Xmeans) / self.Xstds\n",
    "\n",
    "    def use(self, Xnew, k = 1):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        if self.X is None:\n",
    "            raise Exception('KNN object has not been trained yet.')\n",
    "            \n",
    "        self.k = k\n",
    "        # Calc squared distance from all samples in Xnew with all stored in self.X\n",
    "        sqdists = np.sum( (self._standardizeX(Xnew)[:, np.newaxis, :] - self.X)**2, axis=-1 )\n",
    "        # sqdist\n",
    "\n",
    "        # sqdists is now n_new_samples x n_train_samples\n",
    "        # Sort each row of squared distances from smallest to largest and select the first k.\n",
    "        indices = np.argsort(sqdists, axis=1)[:, :k]\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Determine mose common class label in each row.\n",
    "        classes = ss.mode(self.T[indices, :][:, :, 0], axis=1, keepdims=True)[0]\n",
    "        \n",
    "        return classes"
   ]
  },

     ]

   ],
   "source": [
    "pc = []\n",
    "for k in range(1, 21):\n",
    "    pc = percent_correct(knn.use(Xtest, k=k), Ttest)\n",
    "    pc.append([k, pc])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Well, here is what we often face when dealing with big data sets.  K-nearest-neighbors calculates squared distances between each train and test sample. That can get huge.  \n",
    "\n",
    "We can deal with this the typical way of working with batches of data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 144,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T19:40:49.599417Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T19:04:40.920441Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [

     "output_type": "stream",

      "k=16 500,1000,1500,2000,2500,3000,3500,4000,4500,5000,5500,6000,6500,7000,7500,8000,8500,9000,9500,10000,\n",
      "k=17 500,1000,1500,2000,2500,3000,3500,4000,4500,5000,5500,6000,6500,7000,7500,8000,8500,9000,9500,10000,\n",
      "k=18 500,1000,1500,2000,2500,3000,3500,4000,4500,5000,5500,6000,6500,7000,7500,8000,8500,9000,9500,10000,\n",
      "k=19 500,1000,1500,2000,2500,3000,3500,4000,4500,5000,5500,6000,6500,7000,7500,8000,8500,9000,9500,10000,\n",
      "k=20 500,1000,1500,2000,2500,3000,3500,4000,4500,5000,5500,6000,6500,7000,7500,8000,8500,9000,9500,10000,\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "knn = KNN()\n",
    "n_train = 10000\n",
    "knn.train(Xtrain[:n_train, :], Ttrain[:n_train, :])\n",
    "\n",
    "batch_size = 500\n",
    "n_samples = Xtest.shape[0]\n",
    "batches = [batch_size] * (n_samples // batch_size)\n",
    "if sum(batches) < n_samples:\n",
    "    batches = batches.append(n_samples - sum(batches))\n",
    "\n",
    "results = []\n",
    "for k in range(1, 21):\n",
    "    print(f'k={k}', end=' ')\n",
    "    n_correct = 0\n",
    "    first = 0\n",
    "    for this_batch in batches:\n",
    "        last = first + this_batch\n",
    "        print(f'{last}', end=',')\n",
    "        X = Xtest[first:last, :]\n",
    "        T = Ttest[first:last, :]\n",
    "        n_correct += np.sum(knn.use(X, k=k) == T)\n",
    "        first += this_batch\n",
    "    pc = n_correct / n_samples * 100\n",
    "    results.append([k, pc])\n",
    "    print()"
   ]
  },

    "n = 40\n",
    "X = np.random.multivariate_normal([5, 6], [[0.9, -0.2], [-0.2, 0.9]], n)\n",
    "X = np.vstack((X,\n",
    "               np.random.multivariate_normal([6, 3], [[2, 0.4], [0.4, 2]], n)))\n",
    "T = np.vstack((np.ones((n, 1)), 2 * np.ones((n, 1))))\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "m = 100\n",
    "xs = np.linspace(0, 10, m)           \n",
    "ys = xs\n",
    "Xs,Ys = np.meshgrid(xs, ys)\n",
    "samples = np.vstack((Xs.ravel(), Ys.ravel())).T\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(20, 30))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create and train Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)\n",
    "# and Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) Classifiers\n",
    "qda = qdalda.QDA()\n",
    "qda.train(X, T)\n",
    "lda = qdalda.LDA()\n",
    "lda.train(X, T)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create and train k-nearest-neighbor (KNN) classifier\n",
    "knn = KNN()\n",
    "knn.train(X, T)\n",
    "    \n",
    "ploti = 0\n",
    "\n",
    "# Use and plot results for LDA and QDA\n",
    "ploti += 1\n",
    "plt.subplot(5, 3, ploti)\n",
    "classes = lda.use(samples)\n",
    "plot_result(X, Xs, Ys, classes)\n",
    "plt.title('LDA')\n",
    "\n",
    "ploti += 1\n",
    "plt.subplot(5, 3, ploti)\n",
    "classes = qda.use(samples)\n",
    "plot_result(X, Xs, Ys, classes)\n",
    "plt.title('QDA')\n",
    "\n",
    "ploti += 1\n",
    "# Use and plot results for KNN with various values of k\n",
    "for k in [1, 2, 3, 5, 10, 20]:\n",
    "    ploti += 1\n",
    "    plt.subplot(5, 3, ploti)\n",
    "    classes = knn.use(samples, k)\n",
    "    plot_result(X, Xs, Ys, classes)\n",
    "    plt.title(f'KNN k={k}')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Use and plot results for neural networks with various hidden layer structures\n",
    "for n_hiddens in [[], [1], [2], [10], [10, 10], [5, 5, 5, 5]]:\n",
    "    ploti += 1\n",
    "    plt.subplot(5, 3, ploti)\n",
    "\n",
    "    nnet = nn.NeuralNetworkClassifier(2, n_hiddens, 2)\n",
    "    nnet.train(X, T, n_epochs=1000, method='scg', verbose=False)\n",
    "    classes, _ = nnet.use(samples)\n",
    "    plot_result(X, Xs, Ys, classes)\n",
    "    plt.title(f'nnet {n_hiddens}')\n"
   ]
